{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17476845","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17476845"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-28T22:53:23+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-28T22:53:23+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"13958"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"13958","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/13958"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.14,0.69,0.03,0.11,0.03]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"6588"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"111778"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"6588","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/6588"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"13958"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"93848"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"9"},{"type":"tags","id":"20"},{"type":"tags","id":"24"},{"type":"tags","id":"26"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"78"},{"type":"tags","id":"538"},{"type":"tags","id":"1087"},{"type":"tags","id":"4256"},{"type":"tags","id":"4272"},{"type":"tags","id":"4961"},{"type":"tags","id":"4976"},{"type":"tags","id":"4982"},{"type":"tags","id":"4987"},{"type":"tags","id":"4992"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"},{"type":"tags","id":"11630"},{"type":"tags","id":"11635"},{"type":"tags","id":"11642"},{"type":"tags","id":"11650"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"13301"},{"type":"contributions","id":"13930"},{"type":"contributions","id":"44189"},{"type":"contributions","id":"45112"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"111778","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/111778"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA four-year-old boy is brought to a small rural Emergency Department 20 minutes after being involved in an unwitnessed explosion at his family home. He has no significant medical history and takes no regular medications. On examination, he appears alert. His pulse rate is 110/min, blood pressure 100/60 mmHg, respiratory rate 24/min, SpO2 98% on room air and temperature 36.8\u00b0C. He has sustained facial burns with evidence of burns to his eyebrows and eyelashes. There is a non-circumferential burn to the neck. His estimated percentage of body surface area (BSA) burnt is 7%. His parents report that his voice is now \u0027croaky\u0027 and a cough is noticed. He has carbonaceous sputum and singed nasal hairs.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate next step in management?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Administer high-flow oxygen and observe","Perform rapid sequence induction and intubation","Administer nebulised adrenaline","Perform awake fibreoptic intubation","Perform emergency cricothyroidotomy"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis case presents a child with facial burns and clear signs of inhalation injury including hoarse voice, cough, carbonaceous sputum, and singed nasal hairs. These findings indicate significant upper airway involvement that can rapidly progress to complete airway obstruction due to oedema, especially in a child with anatomically smaller airways.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPerform rapid sequence induction and intubation\u003C/strong\u003E is the most appropriate next step. With clear signs of inhalation injury and the potential for rapid deterioration, securing a definitive airway early is crucial. Waiting for signs of respiratory distress may lead to a more difficult intubation as airway oedema progresses. In this rural setting with limited resources, early intubation while the airway is still manageable is the safest approach.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAdminister high-flow oxygen and observe\u003C/strong\u003E would be inadequate management for this patient. While the child currently has normal oxygen saturation, the signs of inhalation injury indicate a high risk for progressive airway compromise. Observation alone could lead to a scenario where emergency intubation becomes necessary under less controlled conditions.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAdminister nebulised adrenaline\u003C/strong\u003E may temporarily reduce airway oedema but does not provide definitive airway management. This would be a temporising measure at best and could give a false sense of security while the underlying pathology progresses.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPerform awake fibreoptic intubation\u003C/strong\u003E would be technically challenging in a four-year-old child, especially in a rural emergency department that may not have paediatric fibreoptic equipment or expertise. Additionally, the child\u0027s cooperation would be limited, making this approach impractical.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPerform emergency cricothyroidotomy\u003C/strong\u003E is not indicated as a first-line approach when the patient still has a patent airway. This invasive procedure carries significant risks, especially in children, and should be reserved for cannot-intubate-cannot-oxygenate scenarios. The anatomical landmarks in children are also more difficult to identify, making this a high-risk procedure.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAfter securing the airway, the next priorities would include arranging urgent transfer to a paediatric burns centre, initiating fluid resuscitation if needed, providing analgesia, and applying appropriate burn dressings. Early involvement of a retrieval team is essential in this rural setting to facilitate transfer to definitive care.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["In a patient with facial burns and signs of inhalation injury, securing the airway is the first priority in management.","Early involvement of a retrieval team is crucial for patients with potential airway compromise in rural settings."],"references":["Sheridan, RL. Inhalation injury from heat, smoke, or chemical irritants. In: UpToDate, Post TW (Ed), UpToDate, Waltham, MA. (Accessed on July 17, 2024)."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"93848"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"13958"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"93848","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/93848"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-08-19T19:22:48+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-08-19T19:24:47+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"6588"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"111778"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"9","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/9"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc76","name":"Paediatrics","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-01-16T08:39:03+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"20","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/20"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc4c","name":"Plastic Surgery","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"2"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"24","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/24"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\ude91","name":"Emergency Medicine","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"d